🔴 Kubernetes Architecture -----------------
  Control Plane (Master Node) – manages the cluster
  Worker Nodes – run the applications (containers)

  1️⃣ Control Plane (Cluster Brain)
    Definition:
    The Control Plane manages the entire Kubernetes cluster and makes decisions like scheduling pods, scaling, and maintaining the desired state.

    🚩Core Components
      1. kube-apiserver
        Entry point of the Kubernetes cluster
        All kubectl commands, API calls, and UI requests go through it
        Validates and processes REST requests
  
        Interview Insight
        No component talks directly with others; everything communicates via API Server.

      2. etcd
        Distributed key-value store
        Stores cluster state and configuration
        
        Examples stored:
        Pods
        Deployments
        Secrets
        ConfigMaps
        Node info
        
        Important
        If etcd is lost → cluster state lost

      3. kube-scheduler
        Decides which node a pod should run on
        
        Scheduling factors:
        CPU / Memory availability
        Node affinity
        Taints & tolerations
        Resource requests

      4. kube-controller-manager
        Runs controllers that maintain desired state.
        
        Examples:
        Node Controller
        Replication Controller
        Endpoint Controller
        Job Controller
        
        Example:
        Desired: 3 pods
        Running: 2 pods
        Controller → creates 1 more pod

  2️⃣ Worker Nodes (Where Applications Run)
    Definition
    Worker nodes are the machines that run the containerized workloads (pods).
  
      Each worker node contains:
      1. kubelet
        Agent running on each node.
        Responsibilities:
        Communicates with API Server
        Ensures containers inside pods are running
        Reports node status
        
        Example:
        API Server → Run pod nginx
        kubelet → pulls image and starts container
      
      2. Container Runtime
        Software responsible for running containers.
        
        Examples:
        containerd
        CRI-O
        Docker (older setups)
        
        Tasks:
        Pull images
        Run containers
        Manage container lifecycle
      
      3. kube-proxy
        Handles network communication inside cluster.
        
        Responsibilities:
        Maintains iptables / IPVS rules
        Enables Service networking
        Load balances traffic between pods
        
        Example:
        Service → nginx-service
        Traffic → kube-proxy → one of the pods

        📌 Real Flow Example
          Request → Service (ClusterIP)
                  ↓
          kube-proxy (on node)
                  ↓
          Selects Pod (load balancing)
                  ↓
          Routes traffic

    3️⃣ How Everything Works Together
      Pod Creation Flow
      
      1️⃣ User runs
        kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
      2️⃣ Request goes to API Server
      3️⃣ API Server stores state in etcd
      4️⃣ Scheduler selects best node
      5️⃣ kubelet on that node receives instruction
      6️⃣ Container Runtime pulls image and runs container
      7️⃣ kube-proxy enables networking

🔴 Pods & Containers ----------------------------------
  🔹 Pod: Smallest deployable unit → wraps one or more containers sharing network & storage
  🔹 Container: Actual application runtime (e.g., app process inside image)
  🔹 Key idea: Containers in same pod share IP, port space, volumes
  🔹 Interview tip: Usually 1 container per pod (multi-container only for sidecar pattern)

🔴 Namespaces -----------------------------------
  🔹 Definition: Logical isolation to separate resources within a cluster
  🔹 Key idea: Same resource names can exist in different namespaces (e.g., dev, prod)
  🔹 Important: Used for multi-team, environment separation + RBAC control
  🔹 Interview tip: Always use namespaces for organization + access control (avoid default)

🔴 Labels & Selectors --------------------------------
  🔹 Labels: Key-value pairs attached to objects (pods, services) for identification/grouping
  🔹 Selectors: Used to filter/select objects based on labels (e.g., Service → Pods)
  🔹 Key idea: Enable loose coupling between components (no hard linking)
  🔹 Interview tip: Wrong labels = Service won’t route traffic (no endpoints)

🔴 kubectl Basics (Kubernetes CLI) ------------------------
  1️⃣ Definition
    kubectl is the command-line tool used to interact with a Kubernetes cluster.
    It communicates with the API Server to create, update, delete, and view cluster resources.

  2️⃣ Kubectl Commands ----
    kubectl get pods: check the pods inside the node
    kubectl get services: check the services 
    kubectl create -h: It will give all available create commands
      clusterrole           Create a cluster role
      clusterrolebinding    Create a cluster role binding for a particular cluster role
      configmap             Create a config map from a local file, directory or literal value
      cronjob               Create a cron job with the specified name
      deployment            Create a deployment with the specified name
      ingress               Create an ingress with the specified name
      job                   Create a job with the specified name
      namespace             Create a namespace with the specified name
      poddisruptionbudget   Create a pod disruption budget with the specified name
      priorityclass         Create a priority class with the specified name
      quota                 Create a quota with the specified name
      role                  Create a role with single rule
      rolebinding           Create a role binding for a particular role or cluster role
      secret                Create a secret using a specified subcommand
      service               Create a service using a specified subcommand
      serviceaccount        Create a service account with the specified name
      token                 Request a service account token
    kubectl create deployment NAME --image=image: to create deplyment using certain docker image [nginx-depl --image=nginx].
    kubectl get deployment: check the deployment
    ImagePullBackOff:  is the system's way of saying: "I tried to download the software for your Pod, but I failed, and I’m tired of trying for a moment."
    minikube start/stop: to start and stop the minikube.
    kubectl get replicaset: 
    kubectl edit deployment nginx-depl: let us edit the deployment
    kubectl logs podName: get the logs of pod to debug
    kubectl describe podName: get the deatiled execution flow and status
    kubectl exec -it PodName -- bin/bash: It allows you to open an interactive terminal session inside the running Pod.
    exit: to exit from terminal.
    kubectl delete deployment mongo-depl: delete the deployment.
    kubectl apply -f config-file.yaml: It will apply the changes to configuration file.

    
    kubectl get all -n kubernetes-dashboard: get all the resources under kubernetes-dashboard
    
    

    kubectl describe service nginx-service: get the deatils of the service
    kubectl get pod -o wide: is the "expert view" for inspecting pods.
    kubectl get deployment nginx-deployment -o yaml
    kubectl get deployment nginx-deployment -o yaml: retrieve the full, "source of truth" document from the etcd database and display it in its raw YAML data structure.
    kubectl get deployment nginx-deployment -o yaml > nginx-deployment-result.yaml: you are instructing your shell to take the Standard Output (stdout) of the kubectl query—which 
                                                                                    contains the full internal representation of your deployment in the cluster—and redirect it 
                                                                                    into a new physical file on your Mac named nginx-deployment-result.yaml.
    head -n 20 nginx-deployment-result.yaml: To verify the file was created and see the first few lines.
    kubectl delete -f <deployment/service config.file>: to delete those files.
    kubectl get all: to get the all component inside cluster/minikube
    echo -n 'username' | base64: binary-to-text encoding (-n: This flag tells echo not to append a trailing newline (\n))
    kubectl get all | grep mongob: get all mongodb ones
    minikube service mongo-express-service: this will assign an external IpAddress.
    kubectl logs -l app=mongodb: selects the pod by its label and show the logs.
    kubectl get svc mongo-express-service: an inspection command used to view the networking details of a specific Service.
    kubectl port-forward svc/mongo-express-service 8081:8081\n: a networking tunnel that creates a direct link between your local machine (MacBook) and a Service inside your Kubernetes cluster.
                                                                Technically, it allows you to access a private cluster resource without setting up a complex LoadBalancer or Ingress.
    kubectl rollout restart deployment mongo-express: the "cleanest" way to reboot your application without changing your configuration or deleting the resource entirely.
