4️⃣ Configuration & Secrets Management

🔴 ConfigMaps ----------------------
  🔹Definition: Stores non-sensitive configuration data (key-value pairs) for pods
  🔹Key idea: Decouples config from container image → no rebuild needed on config change
  🔹Usage: Inject via env variables or mounted files (volumes)
  🔹Interview tip: Use Secrets for sensitive data, ConfigMaps only for plain config

🔴 Secrets (types, encoding) ----------------------
  🔹Definition: Stores sensitive data (passwords, tokens, keys) securely for pods
  🔹Types: Opaque (generic), kubernetes.io/dockerconfigjson (image pull), kubernetes.io/tls (certs), kubernetes.io/service-account-token
  🔹Encoding: Stored as Base64 encoded (not encrypted by default) → enable etcd encryption for real security
  🔹Interview tip: Use Secrets (not ConfigMaps) + mount as volume instead of env for better security

🔴 Environment variables vs volumes ----------------------
  🔹Env Variables: Inject config as key-value at container start → not updated dynamically
  🔹Volumes: Mount config (ConfigMap/Secret) as files → updates can reflect without restart
  🔹Use case: Env → simple configs (flags, URLs) | Volumes → large configs, certs, dynamic updates
  🔹Interview tip: Prefer Volumes for Secrets (more secure & flexible)

🔴 Secret management best practices ---------------
  🔹Avoid plain secrets: Enable etcd encryption at rest + never store secrets in Git (use external vaults)
  🔹Use external secret managers: Integrate with HashiCorp Vault / cloud secret services instead of native Secrets
  🔹Access control: Apply RBAC + least privilege (only required pods/service accounts can read secrets)
  🔹Safer usage: Mount as volumes (not env vars) + rotate secrets regularly
