5️⃣ Scaling, Reliability & Availability (SRE Strength Area)

🔴 Resource requests & limits -----------------
  🔹 Definition: Defines CPU/Memory allocation for containers (requests = minimum, limits = maximum)
  🔹 Key idea: Scheduler uses requests to place pods; limits restrict usage (CPU throttling, memory OOM kill)
  🔹 Important:
    CPU → throttled if exceeds limit
    Memory → container killed (OOMKilled) if exceeds limit
  🔹 Interview tip: Always set requests = guaranteed baseline, limits to prevent noisy neighbor issues

🔴 OOMKill & CPU throttling ---------------------
  🔹 OOMKill: Happens when container exceeds memory limit → Kubernetes kills it (status = OOMKilled)
  🔹 CPU Throttling: When container exceeds CPU limit → CPU is slowed down, not killed
  🔹 Key difference: Memory = hard limit (kill) | CPU = soft limit (throttle)
  🔹 Interview tip: OOMKills indicate bad memory sizing/leaks → fix via proper limits + monitoring

🔴 HPA (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler) -----------------
  🔹 Definition: Automatically scales number of pods (replicas) based on metrics (CPU, memory, custom)
  🔹 Key idea: If load ↑ → pods ↑ | load ↓ → pods ↓ (works with Deployments/ReplicaSets)
  🔹 Important: Requires Metrics Server; uses target like CPU 70% to decide scaling
  🔹 Interview tip: HPA scales pods (horizontal), not resources → combine with VPA for full optimization

🔴 VPA basics ----------------
  🔹 Definition: Automatically adjusts CPU/Memory requests & limits of pods (vertical scaling)
  🔹 Key idea: Instead of adding pods, it resizes existing pods based on usage
  🔹 Modes: Off (recommendation only), Auto (updates + restarts pods), Initial (set at creation only)
  🔹 Interview tip: VPA may restart pods, so avoid using with HPA on same resource (conflict)

🔴 Pod Disruption Budget (PDB) --------------------
  🔹 Definition: Ensures a minimum number of pods stay available during voluntary disruptions (e.g., node drain, upgrades)
  🔹 Key idea: Controls how many pods can go down at a time (minAvailable or maxUnavailable)
  🔹 Important: Applies only to voluntary disruptions (not crashes/OOM)
  🔹 Interview tip: Critical for high availability apps during maintenance (prevents full downtime)

🔴 Node failures & pod rescheduling -----------------
  🔹 Node failure: If a node becomes NotReady/unreachable, pods on that node are considered failed
  🔹 Rescheduling: Controller (Deployment/ReplicaSet) creates new pods on healthy nodes automatically
  🔹 Important: Pods are not moved, they are recreated on other nodes
  🔹 Interview tip: Use multiple replicas + PDB to ensure availability during node failures
