6️⃣ Health Checks & Probes (Asked a LOT)

🔴 Liveness probe -----------------
  🔹 Definition: Checks if a container is still alive (not stuck/deadlocked)
  🔹 Key idea: If probe fails → Kubernetes restarts the container automatically
  🔹 Types: HTTP, TCP, Exec (command inside container)
  🔹 Interview tip: Liveness = restart on failure (don’t confuse with readiness)

🔴 Readiness probe -------------------
  🔹 Definition: Checks if a container is ready to serve traffic
  🔹 Key idea: If probe fails → pod is removed from Service endpoints (no traffic), but not restarted
  🔹 Types: HTTP, TCP, Exec
  🔹 Interview tip: Readiness = traffic control, Liveness = restart control

🔴 Startup probe ---------------
  🔹 Definition: Checks if an application has started successfully (initial boot phase)
  🔹 Key idea: Disables liveness/readiness checks until startup succeeds → avoids premature restarts
  🔹 Use case: Slow-start apps (e.g., JVM, large DB init)
  🔹 Interview tip: Use Startup probe when liveness fails during initial delay/startup time

🔴 Real production use cases ---------------------
  🔹 Liveness Probe:
    Restart stuck apps (e.g., deadlock, memory freeze) → prevents zombie containers in long-running services
  🔹 Readiness Probe:
    Delay traffic until app is fully ready (e.g., DB connection, cache warmup) → avoids serving failed requests
  🔹 Startup Probe:
    Handle slow boot apps (e.g., Java/Spring, large ML models) → prevents false restarts during initialization
  🔹 Interview tip:
    Use all 3 together → Startup (boot) → Readiness (traffic) → Liveness (health) for production-grade reliability
