🧲 Real-time Scenario ------ 
        1️⃣ Issue
        Kubernetes Dashboard not accessible via Ingress and custom domain on Minikube.
        
        2️⃣ Symptoms
        dashboard.com opens blank page or fails to load
        Dashboard not visible despite Ingress controller and DNS mapping
        Service remains inaccessible externally
        
        3️⃣ Root Cause
        Kubernetes Dashboard is not exposed via Ingress by default. On Minikube, Ingress has no real external IP and the dashboard requires authenticated, secure access.
        
        4️⃣ Troubleshooting
        Verified Ingress controller was running
        Confirmed DNS resolution was correct
        Checked dashboard service type (ClusterIP)
        Identified absence of Ingress resource for dashboard
        Observed authentication requirement for dashboard access
        
        5️⃣ Resolution
        Used minikube dashboard, which:
        Starts a local secure proxy on the host machine
        Forwards traffic directly to the dashboard’s ClusterIP service
        Uses current kubeconfig for authentication
        Manages TLS internally
        Opens the dashboard in the browser without external exposure  


🧲 Real-time Scenario ----------------------
      1. Issue
        Ingress controller pod not visible in kube-system namespace after installation.

      2. Symptoms
        kubectl get pods -n kube-system did not show ingress controller pod
        kubectl get pods -A | grep ingress showed ingress controller running

      3. Root Cause
        Ingress controller is not a core Kubernetes component and was installed by Minikube in the ingress-nginx namespace, not kube-system.

      4. Troubleshooting Steps
        Listed pods across all namespaces using <kubectl get pods -A>
        Identified ingress controller running in ingress-nginx namespace
        Verified by running <kubectl get pods -n ingress-nginx>

      5. Resolution
        Confirmed ingress controller was correctly deployed in ingress-nginx; no action required.

🧲 Real-time Scenario 
  🐞 Issue 
    mongo-express UI returns “Unauthorized” after exposing service via Minikube.
  
  📌 Symptoms 
    mongo-express pod was in Running state
    Service was created as NodePort
    Running:
      <minikube service mongo-express-service>
    opened:
      <http://127.0.0.1:<random-port>>
    Browser consistently returned:
      "Unauthorized"
  
  🔍 Root Cause ----------------------
    When using Minikube with Docker/OrbStack driver on macOS, NodePort services are exposed via a local tunnel, which maps the service to a random localhost port.
    The redirection from NodePort → 127.0.0.1:<random-port> was expected behavior, not an error.
    The actual issue was application-level:
    mongo-express enables Basic Authentication by default
    Only MongoDB connection credentials were configured using:
      ME_CONFIG_MONGODB_ADMINUSERNAME
      ME_CONFIG_MONGODB_ADMINPASSWORD
    No UI authentication credentials were configured
    Basic Auth was not explicitly disabled
    As a result, mongo-express rejected all requests with 401 Unauthorized
  
  🛠️ Troubleshooting Steps Taken ----------------------------
    1️⃣ Verified Pod and Service Health
      kubectl get pods
      kubectl get svc mongo-express-service
      Pod was running
      Service existed and correctly mapped
    
    2️⃣ Identified macOS + Minikube NodePort Behavior
      Observed that Minikube exposed the service on:
      http://127.0.0.1:<random-port>
      Confirmed this was expected due to Docker/OrbStack driver
    
    3️⃣ Eliminated Networking as Root Cause
      Used port forwarding to bypass Service and NodePort:
      kubectl port-forward svc/mongo-express-service 8081:8081
      Issue still persisted → confirmed not a Kubernetes networking problem
    
    4️⃣ Inspected Application Configuration
      kubectl describe pod <mongo-express-pod-name>
      Verified environment variables
      Found only MongoDB credentials configured
      No ME_CONFIG_BASICAUTH settings present
    
    5️⃣ Applied Fix (Disable UI Authentication)
      Edited deployment:
      kubectl edit deployment mongo-express
      Added:
        - name: ME_CONFIG_BASICAUTH
          value: "false"
    
    6️⃣ Restarted Application Pods
      kubectl rollout restart deployment mongo-express
    
    7️⃣ Re-tested Access
      kubectl port-forward svc/mongo-express-service 8081:8081
      Accessed:
        http://localhost:8081
        mongo-express UI loaded successfully without Unauthorized
  
    ✅ Final Resolution ----------------------
      The issue was caused by default Basic Authentication enabled in mongo-express
      Explicitly disabling Basic Auth and restarting the pod resolved the issue
      Kubernetes networking and service exposure were functioning correctly
